attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (GNU/Linux), statically linked, no section header

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample is a Linux backdoor/RAT. It establishes persistence by creating a systemd service file in `/usr/lib/systemd/system/` and enabling it via a symlink in `/etc/systemd/system/multi-user.target.wants/`. The malware communicates with a C2 server (IOC: `ns.mlnrm.com`) using a custom UDP-based protocol to receive commands. Key malicious capabilities include spawning a reverse shell (`/bin/bash`) via `forkpty` and executing arbitrary commands using `system()`. It detaches from the terminal using `daemon()` to run in the background.
